const MDXLayout = "wrapper"
export default function MDXContent({
  components,
  ...props
}) {
  return <MDXLayout {...layoutProps} {...props} components={components} mdxType="MDXLayout">

    <h2 {...{
      "id": "our-color-palette"
    }}>{`Our color palette`}</h2>
    <p>{`We use a color palette that places emphasis on important elements and reflects our brand in our digital products.`}</p>
    <p>{`We generally use colors from the Vodafone Brand color palette in a way which supports accessibility. These selected colours provide guidance and help the user to clearly separate content and capture relevant information at first glance. `}</p>
    <h3 {...{
      "id": "brand-colors"
    }}>{`Brand Colors`}</h3>
    <div>
      <img class="img-left-30" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/brand-colors.svg" alt="brand colors" />
      <p>Brand colours are the most representative of the Vodafone brand and should be used with caution as they either attract a lot of attention in a quiet environment or sink into an environment with many coloured areas. Depending on the context, these should always be the first choice before the accent colours.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <h3 {...{
      "id": "accent-colors"
    }}>{`Accent Colors`}</h3>
    <div class="img-left">
      <img class="img-left-30" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/accent-colors.svg" alt="accent colors" />
      <p>Accent colors should be kept to a minimum, we recommend not to use more than three together. These colors serve to identify special offers to the user. These colors can be used discreetly as a background, but are not clickable. </p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div> 
    <h3 {...{
      "id": "functional-colors"
    }}>{`Functional Colors`}</h3>
    <div class="img-left">
      <img class="img-left-30" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/functional-colors.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <p>The notification colours or styles are only used for  respectively boxes or notifications. Our notifications have an assigned color for each feedback, which should not be changed.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <h3 {...{
      "id": "neutral-colors"
    }}>{`Neutral Colors`}</h3>
    <div class="img-left">
      <img class="img-left-30" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/neutral-colors.svg" alt="neutral colors" />
      <p>The neutral colours are used for texts, backgrounds and for navigational elements like tabs and buttons to add depth to our designs as well as help with prioritisation of content.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <h3 {...{
      "id": "gradient"
    }}>{`Gradient`}</h3>
    <div class="img-left">
      <img class="img-left-30-last" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/gradient-colors.svg" alt="gradient colors" />
      <p>Gradients in brand colors or accent colors are used sparingly in digital design and, with a few exceptions, mainly serve as background colors for larger clickable elements. Gradients in neutral colors serve as backgrounds and boundaries for larger backgrounds.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <h2 {...{
      "id": "contrast"
    }}>{`Contrast`}</h2>
    <div class="gradient-box">
      <p class="text-white space-reset">Important information is generally relayed through text. We provide details about Vodafone products and services, and many pages have navigation elements and accordions to allow the user to control when content is displayed to them. We need to have sufficient color contrast for the text to be legible. Therefore, we recommend that all text which acts as a label for a navigation element or provides the user with key information about a product or service should allow sufficient contrast between the colour it is presented in and its background. </p>
    </div>
    <p><strong parentName="p">{`Read also: `}<a parentName="strong" {...{
          "href": "/vf-design-system-v2/docs/accessability"
        }}>{`accessibiliy`}</a></strong></p>
    <h2 {...{
      "id": "color-rules"
    }}>{`Color Rules`}</h2>
    <p>{`The way colors are combined helps convey the overall tone of the page to build brand consistency across all customer experiences.`}</p>
    <div class="col-50-left">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-1-do.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Do</h4>
      <p class="center-text">Primarily we use <b>$neutral-grey-600</b> for texts on bright backgrounds. 
To ensure enough contrast we use for inverted textes <b>$neutral-white</b> and as a higlight in special cases <b>$color-brand-50</b>.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-50-right">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-1-dont.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Don't</h4>
      <p class="center-text">It’s not alowed to use accent colors or functional colors for texts. </p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <div class="col-50-left">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-2-do.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Do</h4>
      <p class="center-text"><b>$neutral-white</b> is the main foreground color for all containing elements (e.g. tables, cards, modals). You may also use other neutral colors like <b>$neutral-grey-25</b> or in special cases <b>$gradient-grey-vertical-down-100</b> and <b>$gradient-grey-vertical-up-100</b>.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-50-right">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-2-dont.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Don't</h4>
      <p class="center-text">In order to guarantee a uniform image of the website, we do not use too many different coloured backgrounds. In addition, there should always be enough contrast between the content and the background.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <div class="col-50-left">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-3-do.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Do</h4>
      <p class="center-text">Always combine colours in such a way that sufficient contrast is created and optimum legibility can be guaranteed.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-50-right">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-3-dont.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Don't</h4>
      <p class="center-text">Never combine accent colors with each other. The contrast between light and dark must always be strong enough. Do not use foreign colors.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <div class="col-50-left">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-4-do.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Do</h4>
      <p class="center-text">Always keep the balance of colors in focus on the brand and neutral colors. The user should see at first glance that this is Vodafone.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-50-right">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-4-dont.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Don't</h4>
      <p class="center-text">Do not use too many and too large accent colors on one side. If possible, use brand colors in the head area.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div>
    <div class="col-50-left">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-5-do.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Do</h4>
      <p class="center-text">For our Design Tokens we use generic names and uniform labels for the specification.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-50-right">
      <img class="col2-img" src="/vf-design-system-v2/img/color-rule-5-dont.svg" alt="functional colors" />
      <h4 class="center-text">Don't</h4>
      <p class="center-text">To avoid errors, please use the specified names of the individual tokens. To ensure that all information can be grasped and understood at a glance, always refer to our labels.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="clearfix"></div>
    </MDXLayout>;
}

;
MDXContent.isMDXComponent = true;
